When these identifiers appear as columns in annotation files the numbers refer to counts of a given gene or annotation in that genome.

Identifier for metagenomic assembled genomes (MAGs) - corresponds to the *bin* column. The contents within the column headers "Genome"; "fasta"; and "Bin Id" are synonymous. The unique identifiers allow data to be connected between different streams. The difference between the headers is due to different sources; the original column headers are maintained in data files to preserve the raw format from the original source. Discrepancies are resolved via script and outputs have consistent column headers. Each identifier has multiple parts separated by underscores or hyphens: (1) river name; (2) year of the study; (3) surface water vs porewater distinction (sw indicating surface water; pp indicating pore water; (4) number in hours; (5) WHONDRS indicating relationship to the Worldwide Hydrobiogeochemistry Observation Network for Dynamic River Systems research consortium; (6) surface water vs porewater distinction (SW indicating surface water; PP indicating pore water); (7) 48  to indicate that the sample is for the 48 Hour study; (8) six digit unique identifier; (9) single letter indicating the method; and (10) bin identifier.
The broad classification of a geographic area according to environmental conditions based on the Koppen climate classification as defined in the "Climate" column header.
Boundaries used to assign compound classes to molecular formula. Boundary sets 1 are Van Krevelen-based (Kim et al. 2003 and Bailey et al. 2017).
Boundaries used to assign compound classes to molecular formula. Boundary sets 1 are Van Krevelen-based (Kim et al. 2003 and Bailey et al. 2017).
Boundaries used to assign compound classes to molecular formula. Boundary sets 3 further integrate stoichiometry to assign modified compound classes (Rivas-Urbach et al. 2018).
The proportion of the watershed that was burned by a wildfire.
Grouped burn percentages in 10% intervals.
Burn severity of each grid (1-low/unburned; 2-low; 3-medium; and 4-high).
Indicates what type of burn occurred in the publication (prescribed or natural).
Indicates whether the site is affected by the wildfire or not.
Carbon atoms in the analyzed molecule. Identified by an algorithm in Kujawinski and Behn 2006 and modified as described in Tfaily et al. 2017.
Carbon atoms in the analyzed molecule. Identified by an algorithm in Kujawinski and Behn 2006 and modified as described in Tfaily et al.; 2017.
Number of carbon (C) atoms in the formula.
Percent total organic carbon in fewer than 2 millimeter sediment samples. This column is called "61033_C_percent" in the published data package; here we dropped the USGS parameter code.
Isotopic atoms in the analyzed molecule. Identified by an algorithm in Kujawinski and Behn 2006 and modified as described in Tfaily et al. 2017.
Site level calcium concentrations.
Watershed scale average calcium concentrations.
Possible known molecules the analyzed molecule could be. Assigned by checking against a known database. Value of -1 when molecule was not checked against database.
